Detailed Description

Sanity check, without prior inclusion of libmesh_config.h.

This file is no typical header file. It is only to be included at the end of an implementation file, so that the proper variations of the InfFE class are instantiated.

The libMesh namespace provides an interface to certain functionality in the library. It provides a uniform init() method that initializes any other dependent libraries (e.g. MPI or PETSC), and a close() method for closing those libraries. It also provides a centralized place for performance logging and other functionality.

Petsc include files.

SLEPc include files.

Trilinos include files.

enum libMesh::SubsetSolveMode

defines an enum for the question what happens to the dofs outside the given subset when a system is solved on a subset.

Enumerator
SUBSET_ZERO 

Set dofs outside the subset to zero.

SUBSET_COPY_RHS 

Set dofs outside the subset to the value of the corresponding dofs of the right hand side.

SUBSET_DONT_TOUCH 

Leaves dofs outside the subset unchanged. This is fastest, but also most confusing because it abandons the property that the solution vector is (theoretically) independent of the initial guess.

SolverPackage libMesh::default_solver_package ( )
Returns
the default solver interface to use. The value depends on which solver packages were available when the library was configured. The command-line is also checked, allowing the user to override the compiled default. For example, –use-petsc will force the use of PETSc solvers, and –use-laspack will force the use of LASPACK solvers.

626  // \p ReferenceCounter only prints its information
627  // when the last created object has been destroyed.
628  // That does no good if we are leaking memory!
629  ReferenceCounter::print_info ();
630 
631 
632  // Print an informative message if we detect a memory leak
633  if (ReferenceCounter::n_objects() != 0)
634  {
635  libMesh::err << "Memory leak detected!"
636  << std::endl;
637 
638 #if !defined(LIBMESH_ENABLE_REFERENCE_COUNTING) || defined(NDEBUG)
639 
640  libMesh::err << "Compile in DEBUG mode with --enable-reference-counting"
641  << std::endl
642  << "for more information"
643  << std::endl;
644 #endif
645 
646  }
647 
648  // print the perflog to individual processor's file.
649  libMesh::perflog.print_log();
650 
651  // Now clear the logging object, we don't want it to print
652  // a second time during the PerfLog destructor.
653  libMesh::perflog.clear();
654 
655  // Reconnect the output streams
656  // (don't do this, or we will get messages from objects
657  // that go out of scope after the following return)
658  //std::cout.rdbuf(std::cerr.rdbuf());
659 
660 
661  // Set the initialized() flag to false
662  libMeshPrivateData::_is_initialized = false;
663 
664  if (libMesh::on_command_line ("--redirect-stdout"))
665  {
666  // If stdout/stderr were redirected to files, reset them now.
667  libMesh::out.rdbuf (out_buf);
668  libMesh::err.rdbuf (err_buf);
669  }
670 
671  // If we built our own output streams, we want to clean them up.
672  if (libMesh::on_command_line ("--separate-libmeshout"))
673  {
674  delete libMesh::out.get();
675  delete libMesh::err.get();
676 
677  libMesh::out.reset(std::cout);
678  libMesh::err.reset(std::cerr);
679  }
680 
681 #ifdef LIBMESH_ENABLE_EXCEPTIONS
682  // Reset the old terminate handler; maybe the user code wants to
683  // keep doing C++ stuff after closing libMesh stuff.
684  std::set_terminate(old_terminate_handler);
685 #endif
686 
687 
688  if (libMesh::on_command_line("--enable-fpe"))
689  libMesh::enableFPE(false);
690 
691 #if defined(LIBMESH_HAVE_PETSC)
692  // Allow the user to bypass PETSc finalization
693  if (!libMesh::on_command_line ("--disable-petsc")
694 #if defined(LIBMESH_HAVE_MPI)
695  && !libMesh::on_command_line ("--disable-mpi")
696 #endif
697  )
698  {
699 # if defined(LIBMESH_HAVE_SLEPC)
700  if (libmesh_initialized_slepc)
701  SlepcFinalize();
702 # else
703  if (libmesh_initialized_petsc)
704  PetscFinalize();
705 # endif
706  }
707 #endif
708 
709 
710 #if defined(LIBMESH_HAVE_MPI)
711  // Allow the user to bypass MPI finalization
712  if (!libMesh::on_command_line ("--disable-mpi"))
713  {
714  this->_comm.clear();
715 #ifndef LIBMESH_DISABLE_COMMWORLD
716  Parallel::Communicator_World.clear();
717 #endif

void libMesh::libmesh_terminate_handler ( )

Definition at line 280 of file libmesh.C.

References GLOBAL_COMM_WORLD, old_terminate_handler, and write_traceout().

281 {
282  // If this got called then we're probably crashing; let's print a
283  // stack trace. The trace files that are ultimately written depend on:
284  // 1.) Who throws the exception.
285  // 2.) Whether the C++ runtime unwinds the stack before the
286  // terminate_handler is called (this is implementation defined).
287  //
288  // The various cases are summarized in the table below:
289  //
290  // | libmesh exception | other exception
291  // -------------------------------------
292  // stack unwinds | A | B
293  // stack does not unwind | C | D
294  //
295  // Case A: There will be two stack traces in the file: one "useful"
296  // one, and one nearly empty one due to stack unwinding.
297  // Case B: You will get one nearly empty stack trace (not great, Bob!)
298  // Case C: You will get two nearly identical stack traces, ignore one of them.
299  // Case D: You will get one useful stack trace.
300  //
301  // Cases A and B (where the stack unwinds when an exception leaves
302  // main) appear to be non-existent in practice. I don't have a
303  // definitive list, but the stack does not unwind for GCC on either
304  // Mac or Linux. I think there's good reasons for this behavior too:
305  // it's much easier to get a stack trace when the stack doesn't
306  // unwind, for example.
307  libMesh::write_traceout();
308 
309  // If we have MPI and it has been initialized, we need to be sure
310  // and call MPI_Abort instead of std::abort, so that the parallel
311  // job can die nicely.
312 #if defined(LIBMESH_HAVE_MPI)
313  int mpi_initialized;
314  MPI_Initialized (&mpi_initialized);
315 
316  if (mpi_initialized)
317  MPI_Abort(libMesh::GLOBAL_COMM_WORLD, 1);
318  else
319 #endif
320  // The system terminate_handler may do useful things like printing
321  // uncaught exception information, or the user may have created
322  // their own terminate handler that we want to call.
323  old_terminate_handler();
324 }

template<typename T >
std::ostream & libMesh::operator<< ( std::ostream &  os,
const SparseMatrix< T > &  m 
)

Same as the print method above, but allows you to print to a stream in the standard syntax.

template <typename u>=""> friend std::ostream& operator << (std::ostream& os, const SparseMatrix<U>& m);

Obscure C++ note 1: the above syntax, which does not require any prior declaration of operator<<, declares any instantiation of SparseMatrix<X> is friend to any instantiation of operator<<(ostream&, SparseMatrix<Y>&). It would not happen in practice, but in principle it means that SparseMatrix<Complex> would be friend to operator<<(ostream&, SparseMatrix<Real>).

Obscure C++ note 2: The form below, which requires a previous declaration of the operator<<(stream&, SparseMatrix<T>&) function (see top of this file), means that any instantiation of SparseMatrix<T> is friend to the specialization operator<<(ostream&, SparseMatrix<T>&), but e.g. SparseMatrix<U> is not friend to the same function. So this is slightly different to the form above...

This method seems to be the "preferred" technique, see http://www.parashift.com/c++-faq-lite/template-friends.html

void libMesh::write_traceout ( )

Writes a stack trace to a uniquely named file if –enable-tracefiles has been set by configure, otherwise does nothing. Note that we append to the trace file rather than overwriting it. This allows multiple traces to be written to the same file.

Parallel::Communicator libMesh::communicator(comm)

Referenced by libMesh::ExactSolution::_compute_error(), libMesh::MeshCommunication::assign_global_indices(), and libMesh::PetscPreconditioner< T >::set_petsc_preconditioner_type().

Parallel::Communicator libMesh::CommWorld

The default libMesh communicator.

If this communicator is disabled, we also disable it as a default argument to functions which accept a default communicator argument. This should expose implicit uses of the default communicator as compile-time rather than run-time errors.

The macro LIBMESH_CAN_DEFAULT_TO_COMMWORLD effects this functionality; it is empty (and so leaves arguments with no default value) if the default is disabled, and it sets something equal to the default otherwise.
